stionRevisions","id":"63363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63363"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with recurrent right upper quadrant pain. Ultrasound imaging reveals multiple gallstones (Image 1). The stones are not visible on the plain radiograph. A laparoscopic cholecystectomy is performed and the yellow-white gallstones are shown (Image 2). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the composition of these gallstones?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Black pigment stones","Cholesterol stones","Brown pigment stones","Calcium carbonate stones","Calcium bilirubinate stones"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Echolesterol stones\u003C/strong\u003E, which are the most common type of gallstone in Western populations (80%). They are characteristically radiolucent and appear yellow-white in colour due to their high cholesterol content.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlack pigment stones\u003C/strong\u003E are small, dark, and multiple, containing calcium bilirubinate. They are often associated with chronic haemolysis. \u003Cstrong\u003EBrown pigment stones\u003C/strong\u003E form due to bacterial infection and stasis in the biliary system. \u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium carbonate stones\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium bilirubinate stones\u003C/strong\u003E are both radio-opaque and appear dark in colour (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for cholesterol stone formation include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFemale sex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EObesity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncreased age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERapid weight loss\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cholesterol stones account for 80% of all gallstones in Western populations","Cholesterol stones are radiolucent and typically appear yellow-white in colour","Risk factors for cholesterol stones include female sex, obesity, and increased age"],"references":["Di Ciaula A, Wang DQ, Portincasa P. An update on the pathogenesis of cholesterol gallstone disease. Curr Opin Gastroenterol. 2018 Mar;34(2):71-80. doi: 10.1097/MOG.0000000000000423. PMID: 29283909; PMCID: PMC8118137.","Chen Y, Kong J, Wu S. Cholesterol gallstone disease: focusing on the role of gallbladder. Lab Invest. 2015 Feb;95(2):124-31. doi: 10.1038/labinvest.2014.140. Epub 2014 Dec 15. PMID: 25502177.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48814"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15425"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21199"},{"type":"media","id":"21200"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21201"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21199"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/P0CuosXf6Rp0UIg6H4XzfxYWuaPlNP.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/P0CuosXf6Rp0UIg6H4XzfxYWuaPlNP.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":588,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21200"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fl1yfZ22YfAXmZn9PMoJ814WZEjOSh.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fl1yfZ22YfAXmZn9PMoJ814WZEjOSh.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"21201","links":